Introduction

Enron was a company that showed tremendous growth and was considered one of the most innovative countries of the time in the 1990s. At around the time of the dot-com economy crash, it was revealed that Enron, through partnerships with other companies, was hiding huge debts and losses. Their equity values was several billion less than what its balance sheet said and Arther Andersen, the company contracted as Enron’s accountants was most likely complicit in the fraud (Background information taken from https://www.npr.org/news/specials/enron/.) I chose this data set as I found I had an interest in social networks, especially in analyzing the results of the various community detection methods. I believe the community detection functions will have some interesting results and I hope that disinct communities will emerge that can represent the various departments of people that worked in the company such as legal and R&D. I am particularly looking forward to seeing a community in the center of the network that represents the executives of the company as they would logically be the ones who were the primary progeniters of the fraud that took place.

Prior Work

The Enron corpus was made public during the legal investigation of the Enron corporation and has subsequently been thoroughly researched within academia including the field of network data science. A group of researchers based in Carnegie Mellon University cleaned the Enron Corpus of duplicate and unnecessary data. They then analyzed scatterplots of the data and saw that messages are distributed exponentially amongst the employees of Enron and observed that a small percentage of users comprise of the majority of email with one person nearing 100,000 emails alone. These researchers were also faced with the task of determining the significance of email threads as larger threads hold more information but can also be succeptible to redundant information. These researchers concluded by saying that one way the data can be used is to better evaluate email classification methods (https://bklimt.com/papers/2004_klimt_ceas.pdf). Another group of researchers at Columbia University developed an algorithm to detect the social hierarhy of users in the data based on the contents of the email. Some metrics used to develop the model include the average response times for emails and by using cliques. The latter was accomplished by creating an undirected network graph from the dataset and using community detection methods to determine the cliques. Using that algoritm researchers were able to reproduce the top of Enron’s corporate ladder with great accuracy, but that accuracy did not extend to lower ranked employees. It is important to note, however, that the algorithm is able to accurately identify the 2-3 most important people in a subset of data (https://academiccommons.columbia.edu/doi/10.7916/D83F4XJ9).

Data

The Enron corpus originially contained the contents of the emails and attachments, but a group of researchers at Carnegie Mellon University (https://bklimt.com/papers/2004_klimt_ceas.pdf and https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~enron/) streamlined the data so that duplicates were removed and it could be easily translated to network data. This data was then taken by another group of researchers (https://arxiv.org/pdf/0810.1355.pdf) who further streamlined to be network data and a large list of directed and unweighted edges with 36,692 nodes and 183,831 edges (there are double the entries in the igraph object as it isa directed graph. It was then publicly posted by the Stanford Network Analysis Project in a format easily usable as network data (http://snap.stanford.edu/data/email-Enron.html.) It originally came as space delimited which I converted into a csv file to be easily read into R with the “readr” library. This dataset is obviously very large and and takes up 14 megabytes as an igraph object in R. Using a simple plot function takes well over 5 minutes to compute and results in a picture without qualitative meaning. Therefore other methods will have to be used to create the network diagrams while the igraph library in R will be used primarily for calculations.

Methods

My main goal when attempting to analyze thhis data was to use community detection methods and try to potentially identify communities that could’ve been more involved in the making of the scandal such as executives. In order to do this I modified the original data set so that insignificant nodes were removed and the Louvain community detection algorithm would only affect the significant nodes thus leading to more significant communties. I removed insignificant nodes by testing the community sizes of the data set if nodes of varying degrees were removed. This method resulted in a very intersting graph in gephi where one community was connected to all the other communities in a hierarchical format giving the sense that they were the most important nodes as they had strong connections to each of the other communities. After employing the community detection algorithm, I ventured farther into the SAND with R book and viewed the coreness measurements for both the original network and the modified network with the degree cutoff. From these graph objects, I was able to create coreness networks which gave a hierarchical overview of the nodes that were the most connected. Through the layout of the colors, one can identify the most significant ID numbers of people that had the most connections. From there, I was able to print these nodes and identify the ID numbers of those that were most connected and most significant in the Enron scandal.

Here I created two objects that contain the coreness data for the undirected Enron igraph objects without a degree cutoff and with the degree cutoff of 30. The original has a very strong right skew due to the large amount of sparse nodes but has a small blip at the end of the x-axis with a cluster of nodes of degrees higher than 40 revealing themselves. The second histogram with the degree cutoff shows the nodes with the higher degrees through the left skew. The degree cutoff evidently did not leave many unconnected nodes.

CorenessLayout = function(g) {
  coreness = graph.coreness(g);
  xy = array(NA, dim=c(length(coreness), 2));
  shells = sort(unique(coreness));
  for(shell in shells) {
    v = 1 - ((shell-1) / max(shells));
    nodes_in_shell = sum(coreness==shell);
    angles = seq(0,360,(360/nodes_in_shell));
    angles = angles[-length(angles)]; #  remove last element
    xy[coreness==shell, 1] = sin(angles) * v;
    xy[coreness==shell, 2] = cos(angles) * v;
  }
  return(xy);
}

The code from this chunk and the two below were taken from https://jcasasr.wordpress.com/2015/02/03/plotting-the-coreness-of-a-network-with-r-and-igraph/. This code produces visuals similar to the gplot.target function in the Social Network Analysis library but is much simpler in computing complexity. It does not actually compute centrality but I believe the visuals it produces are similar to what the gplot.target function would produce.

#  assign colors
colbar = rainbow(max(coreness))
#  create layout
ll = CorenessLayout(enron.u)
plot(enron.u, layout=ll, vertex.size=2, vertex.label = NA, vertex.color=colbar[enron.cores], vertex.frame.color=colbar[enron.cores], main='Full Network Coreness')

The plot above is the entire network. The deeper you go into the graph the higher the coreness of the nodes and the more connected they are. The colors give a sense of clear hierarchy between varying levels of coreness and in all it is a very useful graph, in my opinion, in determining how involved a person was in the Enron scandal.

Discussion

The Enron email data set is full of potential. What I did in this notebook barely scratched the surface. For instance, I was limited by my data set using numbers as identifications for people and thus could not find out the names of people responsible for the debacle. Had there been names instead of numbers I’m sure I would have been able to compare who I found were the people most responsible for the scandal and compare it to what the verdicts were in reality. However, from what I gathered online, the only way to obtain such data is to compile it by myself using the orignial Enron corpus which, I must unfortunately say, I do not yet have the acumen to perform such a task.

As I touched on above, this data has been heavily studied and has been used to create community detection models. This data set is one of the few of its kind in that it represents a corporate network through entirely digital communications. I would even go as far to say that the work I did is trivial to what can be done with data of this scale. For example, as I mentioned above, a group of researchers were able to determine an algorithm that could accurately identify the people that were most influential in a network similar to this. Unfortunately, this algorithm became significantly less accurate the lower down the corporate ladder it tried to predict but it still laid a basis for improvement. With the right tools, I believe that an algorithm can be made to use keywords and linguistic trends to more accurately predict a person’s position and rank within a social network. Such an algorithm would be astronomical and have endless applications from determining the severity of foreign threats by gathering information spread or by adapting computers to better identify human speaking traits and mannerisms.
